Communicated by:
ProMED
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Cropping mustards include a range of species in the genera _Brassica_ and _Sinapis_ (family Brassicaceae). It can be affected by a number of diseases, several of them due to fungi, but some also to due to viruses and bacteria. Most of these pathogens can also infect other brassicas which include many cultivated vegetables and wild weed species. Hence, pathogen reservoirs are rife and disease management for brassica crops can be challenging.

Reliable diagnosis is needed to determine if the problem is indeed due to an infectious agent, caused by external factors or during cultivation. Only then will it be possible to design effective management strategies for the farmers above.

